# Command yq

## What does this command do:

yq is a portable command-line YAML, JSON, XML, CSV, TOML, HCL and properties processor

## Installed from

For Fedora install using: `sudo dnf install yq`
For Raspberry Pi install using:
```
arch="$(dpkg --print-architecture)"

case "$arch" in
  arm64) bin="yq_linux_arm64" ;;
  armhf|armel) bin="yq_linux_arm" ;;
  amd64) bin="yq_linux_amd64" ;;
  *)
    echo "Unsupported architecture: $arch"
    exit 1
    ;;
esac

sudo wget "https://github.com/mikefarah/yq/releases/latest/download/${bin}" -O /usr/local/bin/yq
sudo chmod +x /usr/local/bin/yq
```
For Mac install using: `brew install yq`

## Command path

For Fedora run: `/usr/bin/yq`
For Raspberry Pi run: `/usr/local/bin/yq`
For Mac run: `/usr/local/bin/yq`

## Command documentation

Docs can be found at https://github.com/mikefarah/yq

## Command options

### Flags
    -C, --colors                          force print with colors
    -M, --no-colors                       force print with no colors
    -e, --exit-status                     set exit status if there are no matches or null or false is returned
    -f, --front-matter string             (extract|process) first input as yaml front-matter
    -h, --help                            help for yq
    -I, --indent int                      sets indent level for output (default 2)
    -i, --inplace                         update the file in place of first file given
    -p, --input-format string             [auto|yaml|json|props|csv|tsv|xml|base64|uri|toml|lua|ini] (default "auto")
    -N, --no-doc                          don't print document separators (---)
    -0, --nul-output                      use NUL char to separate values
    -n, --null-input                      don't read input, evaluate expression only (useful for creating docs)
    -o, --output-format string            [auto|yaml|json|props|csv|tsv|xml|base64|uri|toml|shell|lua|ini] (default "auto")
    -P, --prettyPrint                     pretty print, shorthand for '... style = ""'
    -s, --split-exp string                print each result into a file named by expression
    -r, --unwrapScalar                    unwrap scalar, print value with no quotes (default true for yaml)
    -v, --verbose                         verbose mode
    -V, --version                         print version information and quit

### Subcommands
    eval        (default) apply expression to each document in each file in sequence
    eval-all    load all yaml documents of all files and run expression once
    completion  generate autocompletion script for bash/zsh/fish/powershell

### Examples
# Read a value from a YAML file
yq '.key' file.yml

# Read nested value
yq '.parent.child' file.yml

# Update a value in-place
yq -i '.key = "newvalue"' file.yml

# Convert YAML to JSON
yq -o json file.yml

# Convert JSON to YAML
yq -p json -o yaml file.json

# Pretty-print JSON as YAML
yq -P -oy sample.json

# Auto-detect XML input from stdin
cat file.xml | yq -p xml

# Merge two YAML files (eval-all)
yq eval-all '. as $item ireduce ({}; . * $item)' file1.yml file2.yml

# Select array elements matching a condition
yq '.items[] | select(.name == "foo")' file.yml

# Add a new key to all array elements
yq -i '.items[].enabled = true' file.yml

# Delete a key
yq -i 'del(.unwanted)' file.yml

# Create a new YAML document from scratch
yq -n '.name = "test" | .version = "1.0"'

# Output a raw scalar (no quotes)
yq -r '.name' file.yml

# Count array length
yq '.items | length' file.yml

# Extract specific keys from each array element
yq '.items[] | {name: .name, id: .id}' file.yml
